i> (in southern England) and <i>wille</i> (in south western England), from Old English <i>wella</i>, <i>well(e)</i>, <i>wiella</i>, <i>wielle</i>, <i>willa</i>, <i>wyll(a)</i>, <i>wylle</i>. This type of name, a topographic term + <i>-er</i>, is particularly typical of Sussex and its neigbouring counties.","English: occupational name for someone who casts metal or who boils salt, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, a derivative with <i>-er</i> of Old English <i>wellan</i>, <i>wiellan</i> ‘to boil’. Compare 5 below.","North German: variant of   Welle  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Waller IV was born about 1432, in Parham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Richard Waller, Sheriff of Kent, was 39 and his mother, Margaret Waller Gulby, was 25. He married Margaret Hotofte about 1510, in Parham, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Wortham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, and was buried in Wortham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1432–1462":"umbes 1432–1462","1432–1462":"1432–1462","1434–1461":"1434–1461","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1462–1539":"1462–1539","1394–1440":"1394–1440","1408–1493":"1408–1493","1434":"1434","1542":"1542","1432":"1432","1440":"1440","1462":"1462","1461":"1461","1493":"1493","1394":"1394","about 1432":"umbes 1432","1408":"1408","1539":"1539","1490":"1490","Wortham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"